prompt:
Write a complete, three-paragraph summary of the history of the internet, ending with a prediction for 2030.

ABSOLUTE REQUIREMENTS - YOUR RESPONSE WILL BE REJECTED IF YOU VIOLATE THESE:

YOU MUST WRITE EXACTLY 1000-1200 CHARACTERS. COUNT EVERY SINGLE CHARACTER.

WRITE EXACTLY THREE PARAGRAPHS. STOP WHEN YOU REACH 1200 CHARACTERS.

TARGET LENGTH: 1100 CHARACTERS

END WITH A COMPLETE SENTENCE AND A PERIOD (.)

DO NOT STOP WRITING UNTIL YOU REACH AT LEAST 1000 CHARACTERS. THIS IS MANDATORY.

Your response must be substantive and detailed. DO NOT write short summaries.

results.response_preview: The internet's history began in the 1960s with the United States Department of Defense's ARPANET project. This initial network connected four nodes and paved the way for modern networking. In the 1980s, the Internet Protocol (IP) was developed, allowing different networks to communicate with each other.  The World Wide Web was invented in 1989 by Tim Berners-Lee, making it easy for people to access and share information using web browsers and hyperlinks. The internet expanded rapidly in the 1990s, with the widespread adoption of dial-up internet and the emergence of online services like America Online and CompuServe. As broadband internet became more prevalent, online activities like streaming and social media became possible.  The internet will continue to evolve, with advancements in artificial intelligence, the Internet of Things, and 5G networks. By 2030, the internet will be even more integrated into daily life, with increased reliance on cloud computing and virtual reality, and it is likely that the internet will be an essential part of every aspect of life.

Initially designed to facilitate communication between research institutions, ARPANET introduced packet-switching technology, allowing efficient data transmission. By the 1970s, breakthroughs led by computer scientists such as Vint Cerf and Bob Kahn resulted in the development of the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) and Internet Protocol (IP), forming the backbone of modern internet communications. In the 1980s, the introduction of the Domain Name System (DNS) and the transition to a more commercial platform catalyzed its rapid expansion.  The following decade marked the rise of the World Wide Web, developed by Tim Berners-Lee, which revolutionized access to information through web browsers. This ease of use spurred explosive growth, leading to the dot-com boom of the late 1990s, where countless websites emerged, and digital commerce began to flourish. By the early 2000s, social media platforms like Facebook and Twitter transformed how people interacted online, facilitating global connectivity. The smartphone revolution beginning in 2007 further accelerated internet usage, embedding it within daily life.
